    <div class="container">
        <div class="header">
            <h1>International Relations Study Guide</h1>
            <p>Reus-Smit: A Very Short Introduction - Comprehensive Teaching Resource</p>
        </div>

        <div class="nav-tabs">
            <button class="tab-btn active" data-tab="overview">Overview</button>
            <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="chapters">Detailed Chapters</button>
            <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="concepts">Key Concepts</button>
            <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="theories">Theories</button>
            <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="timeline">Historical Timeline</button>
            <button class="tab-btn" data-tab="questions">Discussion Questions</button>
        </div>

        <div class="content-area">
            <!-- Overview Tab -->
            <div id="overview" class="tab-content active">
                <div class="section-title">Course Overview & Central Arguments</div>
                
                <div class="quote-box">
                    "International Relations have no frontiers traced out in reality, they are not and cannot be materially separable from other social phenomena."
                    <div class="author">— Raymond Aron</div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="highlight-box">
                    <h4>Reus-Smit's Revolutionary Approach</h4>
                    <p>Traditional IR scholarship focused too narrowly on external relations between sovereign states. This book argues IR should study <strong>the global organization of political authority</strong> and its human and environmental consequences - a much broader and more historically informed approach.</p>
                </div>

                <div class="stats-grid">
                    <div class="stat-card">
                        <div class="stat-number">~50</div>
                        <div class="stat-label">Years since global sovereignty</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="stat-card">
                        <div class="stat-number">76</div>
                        <div class="stat-label">New states 1946-1975</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="stat-card">
                        <div class="stat-number">3</div>
                        <div class="stat-label">Historical authority forms</div>
                    </div>
                    <div class="stat-card">
                        <div class="stat-number">6</div>
                        <div class="stat-label">Major IR theories</div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                
                <div class="key-points">
                    <div class="point-card">
                        <h4>Central Thesis: Political Authority as Organizing Principle</h4>
                        <p>Political authority = <strong>legitimate political power</strong> (power considered rightful). How authority is organized globally affects individual rights, economic functioning, health/education provision, cultural diversity, environmental protection, and international pathologies like war and refugee crises.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="point-card">
                        <h4>Historical Novelty: Why Current System is Fascinating</h4>
                        <p>Pre-1970s, most humans lived in non-sovereign polities (mostly empires). The global sovereign state system is utterly new - only about 50 years old - raising fundamental questions about its origins, dynamics, consequences, and potential transformation.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="point-card">
                        <h4>Three Historical Configurations</h4>
                        <p><strong>Heteronomy</strong> (medieval): Multiple overlapping authorities without clear boundaries. <strong>Empire</strong> (1500-1945): Single imperial centers ruling diverse peoples. <strong>Sovereignty</strong> (1945-present): Territorial states with exclusive authority.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="point-card">
                        <h4>Current Crisis Indicators</h4>
                        <p>US hegemony waning and contested, multilateral cooperation flagging amid collective challenges (climate, pandemics), re-embrace of narrow sovereignty, populist nationalism reinforcing insularity. Are we witnessing the next great transformation?</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Chapters Tab -->
            <div id="chapters" class="tab-content">
                <input type="text" class="search-box" placeholder="Search chapters..." id="chapterSearch">
                
                <div class="chapter">
                    <div class="chapter-header">
                        <div>
                            <span class="chapter-number">Ch 1</span>
                            <span>What is International Relations?</span>
                        </div>
                        <span class="expand-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="chapter-content">
                        <div class="key-points">
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Traditional Problem</h4>
                                <p>Focused only on external state relations - too limiting. Not all important relations are between states (war on terror involves non-state actors), domestic phenomena can have global impact (Brexit, Trump), the global system only emerged fully post-1945.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>New Definition</h4>
                                <p>Global organization of political authority and its human/environmental consequences. Political authority = legitimate political power (power considered rightful).</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Impact Examples</h4>
                                <p>How authority is organized affects: individual rights, economic functioning, health/education provision, cultural diversity, environmental protection, international pathologies (interstate war, refugee crises).</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="chapter">
                    <div class="chapter-header">
                        <div>
                            <span class="chapter-number">Ch 2</span>
                            <span>Global Organization of Political Authority</span>
                        </div>
                        <span class="expand-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="chapter-content">
                        <div class="key-points">
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Three Types of Institutions</h4>
                                <p><strong>Constitutional:</strong> Define authority distribution (sovereignty today)<br>
                                <strong>Fundamental:</strong> Basic practices (law, diplomacy)<br>
                                <strong>Issue-specific:</strong> Address functional challenges (NPT, UNFCCC)</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Three Historical Maps Analysis</h4>
                                <p><strong>Medieval:</strong> No territorial boundaries, heteronomous organization<br>
                                <strong>1900 Empires:</strong> 16 empires divided world, imperial expansion politics<br>
                                <strong>Modern Europe:</strong> Sovereign states with equal boundaries</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Empire to Sovereignty Transformation</h4>
                                <p>1900: Small sovereign system nested in empires. 1945-1975: Near simultaneous empire collapse and delegitimation. Result: 76 new states, sovereignty as global principle.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="chapter">
                    <div class="chapter-header">
                        <div>
                            <span class="chapter-number">Ch 3</span>
                            <span>Theory is Your Friend</span>
                        </div>
                        <span class="expand-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="chapter-content">
                        <div class="key-points">
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Why Theory Matters</h4>
                                <p>Theory = organized assumptions that help make sense of complexity. For any question, myriad facts available - how decide relevance? Theory is inescapable!</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Six Major Theories</h4>
                                <p><strong>Realism:</strong> Power struggle<br><strong>Liberalism:</strong> Democratic peace<br><strong>Constructivism:</strong> Ideas matter<br><strong>English School:</strong> Anarchical society<br><strong>Feminism:</strong> Gender power<br><strong>Post-colonialism:</strong> Imperial legacies</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Theoretical Eclecticism</h4>
                                <p>No single theory answers all questions. Avoid "Cinderella syndrome" - forcing world into theoretical slipper. Start with questions, then select/combine theories.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="chapter">
                    <div class="chapter-header">
                        <div>
                            <span class="chapter-number">Ch 4</span>
                            <span>War</span>
                        </div>
                        <span class="expand-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="chapter-content">
                        <div class="key-points">
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Four Types of War</h4>
                                <p><strong>Constitution:</strong> Remake authority (Wars of Religion)<br>
                                <strong>Position:</strong> Established units fight (World Wars)<br>
                                <strong>State-Making:</strong> Assert control (genocides, revolutions)<br>
                                <strong>Terrorism:</strong> Clandestine groups force change</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>War Makes States (Tilly)</h4>
                                <p>European rulers needed external + internal wars → required resources → bargains with social groups → taxation for security/rights → constitutional constraints → legitimacy</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Three Means of Control</h4>
                                <p><strong>Jus ad Bellum:</strong> When war legitimate (UN Charter Article 51)<br>
                                <strong>Jus in Bello:</strong> How war fought (Geneva Conventions)<br>
                                <strong>Third Party:</strong> Arbitration, authorization, prosecution</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="chapter">
                    <div class="chapter-header">
                        <div>
                            <span class="chapter-number">Ch 5</span>
                            <span>Economy</span>
                        </div>
                        <span class="expand-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="chapter-content">
                        <div class="key-points">
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Mutual Dependence</h4>
                                <p><strong>Economics needs politics:</strong> Exchange needs norms, money needs state backing, markets need intervention<br>
                                <strong>Politics needs economics:</strong> Legitimacy depends on distribution, crises collapse systems</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Two Globalizations</h4>
                                <p><strong>First (mid-19th-WWI):</strong> 13.9% GDP, agricultural dominated<br>
                                <strong>Second (1945-present):</strong> Peak 27% (2008), manufacturing 65%, digital component</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>US Hegemony & Bretton Woods</h4>
                                <p><strong>Hegemony:</strong> Social status with recognized leadership. <strong>System:</strong> Fixed exchange rates, dollar-gold standard. <strong>Collapse 1971:</strong> Competition, Vietnam costs, OPEC surge</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="chapter">
                    <div class="chapter-header">
                        <div>
                            <span class="chapter-number">Ch 6</span>
                            <span>Rights</span>
                        </div>
                        <span class="expand-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="chapter-content">
                        <div class="key-points">
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Rights as Power-Mediators</h4>
                                <p>Rights alter power relations - normative "trump cards." Therefore breed antagonistic politics and often meet repression. Special rights from positions vs. general rights from being human.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Five Waves of State System Expansion</h4>
                                <p><strong>1648:</strong> Westphalia (religious conscience)<br><strong>1808-25:</strong> Latin America ("rational adults")<br><strong>1919:</strong> Versailles (ethnic self-determination)<br><strong>1945-70:</strong> Decolonization (human rights)<br><strong>1991-92:</strong> Soviet/Yugoslav breakup</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Boomerang Pattern</h4>
                                <p>Domestic groups blocked → reach outside → build networks → mobilize norms → external pressure returns. Example: South African apartheid campaign leading to sanctions and 1991 abolition.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="chapter">
                    <div class="chapter-header">
                        <div>
                            <span class="chapter-number">Ch 7</span>
                            <span>Culture</span>
                        </div>
                        <span class="expand-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="chapter-content">
                        <div class="key-points">
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Culturalist vs. Institutionalist Debate</h4>
                                <p><strong>Culturalist:</strong> Cultural unity needed for stable system (Wight, Trump)<br>
                                <strong>Institutionalist:</strong> Institutions hold diverse systems together (Obama)<br>
                                <strong>Both flawed:</strong> Culture never unified; institutions organize rather than neutralize culture</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Diversity Regimes</h4>
                                <p>Norms/practices defining legitimate power centers and relating them to cultural identity. Examples: Ottoman millet system, Qing Eight Banners, modern multiculturalism vs. assimilation.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Rethinking Westphalian "Miracle"</h4>
                                <p>Wasn't pluralist moment - established diversity regime approving only select Christian confessions. Excluded Judaism, Islam, heretical sects. Created hierarchies and exclusions, ignored imperial context.</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="chapter">
                    <div class="chapter-header">
                        <div>
                            <span class="chapter-number">Ch 8</span>
                            <span>An Essential Political Science</span>
                        </div>
                        <span class="expand-icon">▼</span>
                    </div>
                    <div class="chapter-content">
                        <div class="key-points">
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Core Argument Restated</h4>
                                <p>IR should focus on global organization of political authority and its consequences, not just external state relations. This brings historical variety into view and shows current system's uniqueness.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Bold Claim: THE Essential Political Science</h4>
                                <p>Global authority organization conditions all local politics. IR addresses macro-conditions that shape everything else. Makes IR as vital as it is fascinating.</p>
                            </div>
                            <div class="point-card">
                                <h4>Current Crisis Elements</h4>
                                <p>US hegemony waning, multilateral cooperation flagging, narrow sovereignty re-embraced, populist nationalism reinforcing insularity. Next great transformation?</p>
                            </div>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Concepts Tab -->
            <div id="concepts" class="tab-content">
                <input type="text" class="search-box" placeholder="Search concepts..." id="conceptSearch">
                <div class="concept-grid">
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h3>Political Authority</h3>
                        <p>Legitimate political power; power considered rightful. The central organizing principle of all political arrangements.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h3>Sovereignty</h3>
                        <p>Supreme authority within territory, no higher authority above. Today's constitutional institution.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h3>Heteronomy</h3>
                        <p>Multiple overlapping authorities without clear territorial boundaries (medieval Europe).</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h3>Hegemony</h3>
                        <p>Recognized leadership with special rights and responsibilities, not just material primacy.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h3>Anarchy</h3>
                        <p>Absence of central authority (not chaos). Realists argue this forces self-help behavior.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h3>Security Dilemma</h3>
                        <p>When states' security efforts inadvertently threaten others, leading to arms races.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h3>Democratic Peace</h3>
                        <p>Liberal theory that democracies don't fight each other because citizens bear war costs.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h3>Diversity Regimes</h3>
                        <p>Norms defining legitimate power centers and relating them to cultural identity.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="concept-card">
                        <h3>Boomerang Pattern</h3>
                        <p>How domestic groups use international networks to pressure violator states.</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Theories Tab -->
            <div id="theories" class="tab-content">
                <div class="section-title">Six Major Theoretical Perspectives</div>
                <div class="responsive-table">
                    <table>
                        <thead>
                            <tr>
                                <th>Theory</th>
                                <th>Core Claim</th>
                                <th>Key Concepts</th>
                                <th>View of Authority</th>
                            </tr>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <tr>
                                <td><span class="theory-highlight">Realism</span></td>
                                <td>IR is struggle for power in anarchic system</td>
                                <td>Balance of power, security dilemma, hegemonic stability</td>
                                <td>Order requires hegemonic leadership and grand bargain</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><span class="theory-highlight">Liberalism</span></td>
                                <td>Individuals primary, democratic/commercial peace</td>
                                <td>Social contract, rule of law, interdependence</td>
                                <td>Legitimate states need popular sovereignty</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><span class="theory-highlight">Constructivism</span></td>
                                <td>Ideas and social meanings equal to material power</td>
                                <td>Social construction, norms, identities shape interests</td>
                                <td>Authority shaped by shared ideas and values</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><span class="theory-highlight">English School</span></td>
                                <td>States form "anarchical society"</td>
                                <td>International society, recognition, institutions</td>
                                <td>International society ordains sovereign rights</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><span class="theory-highlight">Feminism</span></td>
                                <td>Gender power differentials central to IR</td>
                                <td>Male dominance, gendered knowledge systems</td>
                                <td>All authority configurations privilege male control</td>
                            </tr>
                            <tr>
                                <td><span class="theory-highlight">Post-colonialism</span></td>
                                <td>Imperial legacies and racial hierarchies persist</td>
                                <td>Decentering West, "color line," hierarchies</td>
                                <td>Formal equality masks persistent racial hierarchies</td>
                            </tr>
                        </tbody>
                    </table>
                </div>
