            <!-- Timeline Tab -->
            <div id="timeline" class="tab-content">
                <div class="section-title">Historical Transformation of Political Authority</div>
                <div class="timeline">
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <h3>1648 - Peace of Westphalia</h3>
                        <p><strong>Context:</strong> Protestant Reformation challenged Catholic authority. Wars killed 8 million people.</p>
                        <p><strong>Settlement:</strong> Invested princes with sovereign-like rights, upheld individual religious conscience. Only approved select Christian confessions.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <h3>1808-1825 - Latin American Independence</h3>
                        <p><strong>Spark:</strong> Napoleon's invasion of Spain. Debate over who counted as "rational adults" - Spanish blood only vs. including Indians and freed slaves.</p>
                        <p><strong>Result:</strong> 1812 Constitution denied Americans representation, leading to 15 new states by 1825.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <h3>1919 - Versailles Settlement</h3>
                        <p><strong>Principle:</strong> Europe reorganized on ethnic self-determination, but imperial face maintained for colonies.</p>
                        <p><strong>Legacy:</strong> "Standard of civilization" continued civilized/barbarian distinctions.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <h3>1945-1970 - Decolonization</h3>
                        <p><strong>Scale:</strong> 76 new sovereign states. Empire transformed from "sacred trust" to "crime."</p>
                        <p><strong>Rights Role:</strong> Post-colonial states led human rights codification. Decolonization rate tripled after 1960.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <h3>1991-1992 - Soviet/Yugoslav Breakup</h3>
                        <p><strong>Completion:</strong> Sovereignty becomes global organizing principle with ~200 states and no competing empires.</p>
                    </div>
                    <div class="timeline-item">
                        <h3>2008-Present - Current Crisis?</h3>
                        <p><strong>Challenges:</strong> US hegemony waning, multilateral cooperation flagging, populist nationalism rising.</p>
                        <p><strong>Question:</strong> Next great transformation of global political authority?</p>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>

            <!-- Discussion Questions Tab -->
            <div id="questions" class="tab-content">
                <div class="section-title">Discussion Questions by Theme</div>
                
                <div class="discussion-questions">
                    <h3>Foundational Questions</h3>
                    <div class="question">
                        <strong>1.</strong> How does Reus-Smit's definition of IR as "the global organization of political authority" differ from traditional approaches? What are the advantages and limitations?
                    </div>
                    <div class="question">
                        <strong>2.</strong> Why does the author argue that today's sovereign state system is "fascinating" precisely because of its novelty rather than its naturalness?
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="discussion-questions">
                    <h3>Historical Analysis</h3>
                    <div class="question">
                        <strong>3.</strong> Compare the three historical maps (medieval heteronomy, 1900 empires, modern Europe). What can this evolution tell us about possible future transformations?
                    </div>
                    <div class="question">
                        <strong>4.</strong> Why did all European empires collapse nearly simultaneously after WWII? Evaluate the role of rights discourse versus material factors.
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="discussion-questions">
                    <h3>Theoretical Applications</h3>
                    <div class="question">
                        <strong>5.</strong> If theory is "inescapable," how should we evaluate competing theoretical perspectives? Can they be combined?
                    </div>
                    <div class="question">
                        <strong>6.</strong> How do feminist and post-colonial theories challenge realist and liberal assumptions about political authority?
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="discussion-questions">
                    <h3>Contemporary Issues</h3>
                    <div class="question">
                        <strong>7.</strong> How does the concept of "diversity regimes" explain current tensions around immigration and nationalism?
                    </div>
                    <div class="question">
                        <strong>8.</strong> Given declining interstate wars but persistent civil conflicts, what does this suggest about sovereignty and violence?
                    </div>
                </div>

                <div class="discussion-questions">
                    <h3>Critical Analysis</h3>
                    <div class="question">
                        <strong>9.</strong> Is the author's claim that IR is "the essential political science" justified? What are the implications?
                    </div>
                    <div class="question">
                        <strong>10.</strong> How might China's rise challenge not just Western power but the institutional framework of political authority?
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>

    <script>
        // Wait for DOM to be fully loaded
        document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', function() {
            
            // Tab switching functionality
            const tabButtons = document.querySelectorAll('.tab-btn');
            const tabContents = document.querySelectorAll('.tab-content');
            
            tabButtons.forEach(button => {
                button.addEventListener('click', function() {
                    const targetTab = this.getAttribute('data-tab');
                    
                    // Remove active class from all buttons and contents
                    tabButtons.forEach(btn => btn.classList.remove('active'));
                    tabContents.forEach(content => content.classList.remove('active'));
                    
                    // Add active class to clicked button and corresponding content
                    this.classList.add('active');
                    document.getElementById(targetTab).classList.add('active');
                });
            });
            
            // Chapter expansion functionality
            const chapters = document.querySelectorAll('.chapter');
            chapters.forEach(chapter => {
                const header = chapter.querySelector('.chapter-header');
                header.addEventListener('click', function() {
                    chapter.classList.toggle('expanded');
                });
            });
            
            // Search functionality for chapters
            const chapterSearch = document.getElementById('chapterSearch');
            if (chapterSearch) {
                chapterSearch.addEventListener('input', function(e) {
                    const searchTerm = e.target.value.toLowerCase();
                    chapters.forEach(chapter => {
                        const text = chapter.textContent.toLowerCase();
                        if (text.includes(searchTerm) || searchTerm === '') {
                            chapter.style.display = 'block';
                        } else {
                            chapter.style.display = 'none';
                        }
                    });
                });
            }

            // Search functionality for concepts
            const conceptSearch = document.getElementById('conceptSearch');
            if (conceptSearch) {
                conceptSearch.addEventListener('input', function(e) {
                    const searchTerm = e.target.value.toLowerCase();
                    const concepts = document.querySelectorAll('.concept-card');
                    
                    concepts.forEach(concept => {
                        const text = concept.textContent.toLowerCase();
                        if (text.includes(searchTerm) || searchTerm === '') {
                            concept.style.display = 'block';
                        } else {
                            concept.style.display = 'none';
                        }
                    });
                });
            }
        });
    </script>
</body>
</html>
